From: Sama Engine <engine@local>
Subject: [PATCH] vs_skybox: extract camera world pos via mul(), not column element access

Context — the bug
-----------------
On macOS / Metal, SkyboxRenderer paints the entire viewport with a single
uniform colour matching whichever cube face the camera is currently
pointing at — the skybox is sampled with a constant direction across
every fragment.  GLSL desktop, Vulkan SPIRV, and Android GLES all render
the cubemap correctly; only the Metal backend is affected.

First seen in sama dfd4162 (when SkyboxRenderer + vs_skybox.sc landed).
Reproduced on macOS 14 / M-series / Metal by sample_game integrators.

Root cause
----------
vs_skybox.sc:34 reads the camera world position as direct column element
access:

    vec3 camPos = vec3(u_invView[3][0], u_invView[3][1], u_invView[3][2]);

In GLSL with column-major matrices (bgfx default), u_invView[3] is the
4th column (the translation column) and [col][row] indexing returns
(Tx, Ty, Tz) — the camera world position.  The desktop-GLSL and
Vulkan-SPIRV outputs of bgfx-shaderc preserve this access pattern
faithfully.

bgfx's spirv-cross MSL emitter, however, transcribes the access as:

    float3(_mtl_u.u_invView[0u][3], _mtl_u.u_invView[1u][3], _mtl_u.u_invView[2u][3])

— reading the matrix's bottom row instead of its translation column.
For an affine view matrix the bottom row is (0, 0, 0, 1), so:

    camPos = vec3(0)
    v_worldPos = nearWorld - vec3(0) = nearWorld

`nearWorld` is `camera_world + perpendicular_offset × near_distance`,
where the perpendicular offset is ~tan(fov/2) × near (order ~0.02-0.04
units) and the camera position itself is several units long.  After the
fragment shader's normalize(), the result is dominated by the camera
position vector — every fragment receives essentially the same direction,
so every fragment samples the same cube face.

Confirmed by replacing the fragment textureCube() with
`gl_FragColor = vec4((dir + 1.0) * 0.5, 1.0)` — viewport renders as a
single solid colour with the broken camPos, and as a proper screen-space
gradient with the fix.

The fix
-------
Replace element-wise access with a matrix-vector multiply that
transforms the origin to world space — mathematically identical, but
spirv-cross emits a clean matrix-vector mul on every backend:

    vec3 camPos = mul(u_invView, vec4(0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0)).xyz;

GLSL / SPIRV / ESSL outputs unchanged after compile (the optimizer
collapses the multiply by zero columns).  MSL output now reads the
translation column correctly and the cubemap renders with per-pixel
direction.

Audit
-----
The same `u_invView[3][i]` pattern doesn't appear elsewhere in
`engine/shaders/`; vs_skybox.sc:34 was the only site.  Future shader
authors should prefer `mul(M, vec4(0,0,0,1)).xyz` over direct column
element access when extracting a matrix translation, to insulate the
shader from spirv-cross's MSL emit quirks.  See docs/NOTES.md
"Skybox renders uniform colour on Metal (2026-06-18)".

Acceptance
----------
1. Load sample_game on macOS / Metal at level 0.
2. The plank ball-roll scene should sit on a grass-coloured ground with
   sky and trees visible in the background (assets/textures/skyboxes/park.ktx).
3. Sample any background pixel as the camera moves — colour should
   change per-pixel and per-frame, not remain a constant face hit.

Verified upstream on the sama side
----------------------------------
- All four shader backends recompile clean (vs_skybox_mtl / _spv /
  _glsl / _essl) with no errors or warnings.
- engine_tests 26981 assertions across 753 test cases still pass
  (this is a runtime visual bug; no unit-test regression possible).
- Visual verification requires sample_game on macOS — the engine repo
  itself has no demo wiring the SkyboxRenderer; the editor uses it
  but launches by default at no-level state.

---
 engine/shaders/vs_skybox.sc | 11 ++++++++---
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/engine/shaders/vs_skybox.sc b/engine/shaders/vs_skybox.sc
--- a/engine/shaders/vs_skybox.sc
+++ b/engine/shaders/vs_skybox.sc
@@ -10,9 +10,9 @@
 //
 // We unproject the near-plane point at each vertex through the inverse
 // view-projection matrix to recover its world-space position, then
-// subtract the camera world position (recovered from u_invView's
-// translation column) to get a direction from the camera into the world.
-// The fragment shader uses that direction to sample the cubemap.
+// subtract the camera world position (the origin transformed by u_invView)
+// to get a direction from the camera into the world.  The fragment shader
+// uses that direction to sample the cubemap.
 //
 // gl_Position.z = gl_Position.w forces fragment depth to exactly 1.0
 // after the perspective divide so the skybox sits at the far plane.
@@ -30,8 +30,13 @@
     vec4 nearWorld = mul(u_invViewProj, vec4(a_position.xy, 0.0, 1.0));
     nearWorld.xyz /= nearWorld.w;

-    // Camera world position is the translation column of u_invView.
-    vec3 camPos = vec3(u_invView[3][0], u_invView[3][1], u_invView[3][2]);
+    // Camera world position = origin transformed by u_invView.  Do NOT
+    // read the translation as u_invView[3].xyz element-by-element:
+    // bgfx's spirv-cross MSL emitter transcribes u_invView[3][0..2] as
+    // u_invView[0..2][3] (the bottom row, all zeros for an affine view),
+    // producing camPos = vec3(0) on Metal and uniform-direction skybox.
+    // mul() is layout-agnostic and emits correctly on all backends.
+    vec3 camPos = mul(u_invView, vec4(0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0)).xyz;

     v_worldPos = nearWorld.xyz - camPos;
 }
